, marked both by scheming and absurdity, and the legal inquest that followed, to show how stories of this kind are conceived, told, circulated, and believed. She reveals how the story of Sebastian, supposedly in hiding and planning to return to claim his crown, was lodged among other familiar stories: prophecies of returned leaders, nuns kept against their will, kidnappings by Moors, miraculous escapes, and monarchs who die for their country. As MacKay demonstrates, the conspiracy could not have succeeded without the circulation of news, the retellings of the fatal battle in well-read chronicles, and the networks of rumors and correspondents, all sharing the hope or belief that Sebastian had survived and would one day return. With its royal intrigues, ambitious artisans, dissatisfied religious women, and corrupt clergy, The Baker Who Pretended to Be King of Portugal will undoubtedly captivate readers as it sheds new light on the intricate political and cultural relations between Spain and Portugal in the early modern period and the often elusive nature of historical truth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aking sebastian, portugal, moors, morocco, religion, infidel, spirituality, christianity, islam, war, battle, imposter, gabriel de espinosa, baker, soldier, military, leadership, friar, monarch, monarchy, conspiracy, folklore, royalty, intrigue, coup, ana of austria, don antonio, fray miguel, castile, madrigal, nonfiction, history, politics, kingdom, 1683 pamphlet, identity, kidnapping, returned leaders, arthurian legends, sacrifice, patriotism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022650108640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226501109423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cov